# Assertions in Selenium

1️⃣ What is Assertion?
An assertion is used to verify whether the actual result is equal to expected result.
In Automation testing , assertions help us check if the application is working correctly.
If the condition is True -> Test pass
If the condition is False -> Test failed

Example:
    assert.driver.title == "Google"
This checks whether the page title is Google or not.

2️⃣ Why Assertions Are Important
Assertions are used to:
    1. Validation -> Check if application work correctly
    2. Test Results -> Decide whether the test passes or fails.
    3. Bug Detection -> Helps find issues in the application
    4. Automation Reliability -> Ensures expected behavior

3️⃣ Assertions in Selenium Python
In Python Selenium , assertions are usually used with:
    1. Python built-in assert statement
    2. Testing frameworks like:
        1. unittest
        2. pytest

    Most selenium python tests use assert or unittest assertions.

4️⃣ Basic Python Assertion
    Syntax:
        assert condition
    
    Example:
        assert 5>3
    
    If condition is True -> Pass
    If condition is False -> AssertionError

5️⃣ Assertion with Message
You can add custom assertion error message
    Example:
        assert driver.title == "Google" , Title does not match"
    If the title is wrong , the message will be shown.

6️⃣ Common Assertions in Selenium Python
    1️⃣ Verify Page Title
    assert driver.title == "Google"

    2️⃣ Verify Element Text
    text=driver.find_element(By.ID , "welcome").text
    assert text == "Welcome"

    3️⃣ Verify Element is Displayed
    element=driver.find_element(By.ID , "login")
    assert element.is_displayed()

    4️⃣ Verify URL
    element = driver.find_element(By.LINK_TEXT , "dashboard")
    assert "dashboard" in driver.current_url

    5️⃣ Verify Element Exists
    element=driver.find_element("id" , "username")
    assert element is not None

7️⃣ Example Selenium Script with Assertion
Example Verify Google title

from selenium import WebDriver
driver=WebDriver.FireFox()
driver.get("https://www.google.com")
assert driver.title == "Google"  , "Title is incorrect"
driver.quit()

Explanation:
    1. Open browser
    2. Go to google
    3. Check page title
    4. If title matches -> Test pass
    5. If title does not match -> Test failed

8️⃣ Assertions using unittest
Python unittest framework provides more assertion methods.
Example:
    import unittest
    from selenium import WebDriver

    Class TestGoogle(unittest.TestCase):
        def test_title(self):
            driver=webdriver.FireFox()
            driver.get("https://www.google.com")

            self.assertEqual(driver.title , "Google")
            driver.quit()
    if __name__ == "__main__":
        unittest.main()

9️⃣ Common unittest Assertions
Method & Purpose
-----------------
1. assertEqual(a , b) -> Check if values are equal
2. assertNotEqual(a , b) -> Check values are not equal
3. assertTrue(x) -> Check condition is True
4. assertFalse(x) -> Check condition is False
5. assertIsNone(x) -> Check object is None
6. assertIsNotNone(x) -> Check object is not None

Example:
    self.assertTrue(element.is_displayed())

